\parai{Correctness} refers to the extent to which the information returned is correct. SEs and KGs 
 store explicit representations of their (indexed) contents: full text documents, tables and nodes/edges. LLMs, on the other hand, only capture statistical patterns from the input corpus that can be used to generate text following patterns similar to the input. 
 These patterns are stored in latent form, encoded in the values of billions of model parameters.
 Thus while imprecise answers generated by SEs and KGs can usually be traced back to issues with the input corpus, LLMs may generate imprecise results, hallucinations, etc., not supported at all by their input data. 
 As a consequence, LLMs can perform poorly regarding topics with few supporting documents (i.e., long-tail topics) [DBLP:conf/acl/MallenAZDKH23].